Caption: TWRA's Freddy Kelley uses a drip torch to administer the prescribed fire Monday, March 20, 2017, on Thief Neck Island in Roane County. Prescribed fires prepare sites for seeding of native grasses, control insects and diseases, as well as, improving habitats and enhancing the aesthetics and access for recreation. If left unchecked, invasive species can choke-out native plant species harming the Valley’s eco-system. (Photo: Shawn MIllsaps/Special to the News Sentinel)
Credit/Source: (Photo: Shawn MIllsaps/Special to the News Sentinel)

Caption: TVA's Randy Short holds a devise that measures humidity levels in the air as TVA, TWRA and Tennessee Forestry Department conduct a prescribed fire on Thief Neck Island in Roane County, Tenn., Monday, March 20, 2017. Prescribed fires prepare sites for seeding of native grasses, control insects and diseases, as well as, improving habitats and enhancing the aesthetics and access for recreation. If left unchecked, invasive species can choke-out native plant species harming the Valley’s eco-system. (Photo: Shawn MIllsaps/Special to the News Sentinel)
Credit/Source: (Photo: Shawn MIllsaps/Special to the News Sentinel)

Caption: Ashley and Kevin McAlpin, owners of McAlpin Creative, with one of their customized DIY trays. “We do everything as a partnership,” said Ashley. “Kevin does the woodcutting and preparation. Then I do the vinyl stencil cutting and put the kits together. I also handle the marketing and getting our voice out there.” (Photo: Winx Photo)

Each DIY tray kit can be ordered individually, allowing each crafter to select a different design to stencil on their tray. Simply type in the text to incorporate into the stencil design. (Photo: Winx Photo)
McAlpin Creative DIY kits are a great project for girls’ crafting parties, family get-togethers and even date night, according to co-founder Ashley McAlpin. (Photo: Winx Photo)

The McAlpin Creative kits use water soluble products. “Stains can be smelly or flammable,” said Ashley McAlpin. “We wanted a solution that we could ship without concern that children could use and make clean up easy.”
Each DIY tray kit can be ordered individually, allowing each crafter to select a different design to stencil on their tray. Simply type in the text to incorporate into the stencil design.
The McAlpins have videos on their website to walk people through the assembly and decorating steps.

The online ordering system allows customers to order the same project for everyone, or the party host can send a link out for their guest to order and pay for the design they want. “It takes the stress out of one person having to buy all of them,” said Ashley McAlpin.
McAlpin Creative DIY kits are a great project for girls’ crafting parties, family get-togethers and even date night, according to co-founder Ashley McAlpin.

“All that you need is a screwdriver. All of the wood is precut, sanded and pre-drilled,” said McAlpin. “We have instructional videos online to show you how to stain the wood, build the tray or sign, put handles on the tray, then apply the vinyl stencil and paint your design.”

Ashley and Kevin McAlpin, owners of McAlpin Creative, with one of their customized DIY trays. “We do everything as a partnership,” said Ashley. “Kevin does the woodcutting and preparation. Then I do the vinyl stencil cutting and put the kits together. I also handle the marketing and getting our voice out there.”

Caption: Naturalist Stephen Lyn Bale leads a group of summer campers through a winding creek in search of aquatic creatures.
During “Aquatic Adventures” week at Ijams, summer campers will look for plants and animals that call the ponds, creek and river home.
Ijams Nature Center partners with River Sports Outfitters to provide camp staff training and outdoor recreational equipment, such as stand-up paddle boards, to explore nature.
Campers will take an introductory paddling lesson at Meads Quarry before launching their canoe from the new dock at Ijams Nature Center on the Tennessee River.

A growing individual confidence, learning group cooperation, developing outdoor skills and environmental responsibility are just some of the things that campers will take home with them from the Summer Nature Camp at Ijams Nature Center.

Caption: Pit Crew's Andrew Dacus siphons out the oil of a Toyota in its owner's driveway in Knoxville on Tuesday, October 16, 2018. Pit Crew is an on demand mobile auto service that can perform oil changes, tire rotations and wiper blade replacements wherever is most convenient to the customer.
Our prices are highly competitive for the convenience we offer,” said Pit Crew’s Andrew Dacus, pictured left with Josh Tillery.
Ideally Pit Crew can change oil anywhere with a relatively flat surface and enough “wriggle room” around the car.
Customized stickers show that Pit Crew has completed the service as requested.

Pit Crew launched six months ago and currently has one truck, but post-holiday season, they have seen a serious uptick in business. The owners know it’s only a matter of time before they need to add another van to create a Pit Crew fleet.

Pit Crew's Andrew Dacus, left, and Josh Tillery, right, work on a Toyota in its owner's driveway in Knoxville on Tuesday, October 16, 2018. Pit Crew is an on demand mobile auto service that can perform oil changes, tire rotations and wiper blade replacements wherever is most convenient to the customer.

Pit Crew is an on demand mobile auto service that can perform oil changes, tire rotations and wiper blade replacements wherever is most convenient to the customer.

“Oil changes are our bread and butter, with tire rotations and wiper blade installation close behind,” said Andrew Dacus. Other options offered by Pit Crew include an annual oil change and buy-three-get-one free special packages.

Black eyeglasses mark the trek to the site of a 1959 plane crash that killed Buddy Holly, The Big Bopper, Ritchie Valens and the pilot. The site in Clear Lake, Iowa, and the Surf Ballroom where the trio performed, remain famous as the 60th anniversary of the crash approaches Feb. 3.

Caption:
Pellissippi State Community College student Kristy Hilliard studies inside the J.L. Goins Administration building at the college's Hardin Valley campus on Tuesday, February 4, 2014. Governor Bill Haslam proposed the "Tennessee Promise", a program that will provide two free years of community college or trade school for high school graduates.

(SAUL YOUNG/NEWS SENTINEL)

President Barack Obama greets people on stage as he arrive to speaks at Pellissippi State Community College, Friday, Jan. 9, 2015, in Knoxville, Tenn., about new initiatives to help more Americans go to college and get the skills they need to succeed. (AP Photo/Carolyn Kaster)

Pellissippi State Community College Culinary Arts student Alexis Meneese prepares signature desserts for a community event. The college’s Culinary Arts Institute gained accreditation through the American Culinary Federation Accrediting Commission. It prepares students to earn an Associate of Applied Science degree in Business with a concentration in Culinary Arts.

Members of Pellissippi State Community College.

The annual Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr. Memorial Parade starts at 10am at Tabernacle Baptist Church, 2137 Martin Luther King, Jr., Blvd. and ended at Greater
Warner Tabernacle AME Zion Church, 3800 Martin Luther King Jr. Avenue. Hundreds of people and groups  including local elected officials marched the one and a half miles from start to finish. After the parade the Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr. Memorial Service was held at the Warner Tabernacle AME Zion Church with  Rev. Dr. Charles E. Goodman, Jr., senior pastor of Tabernacle Baptist Church in Augusta, Ga., is the guest speaker.
Music by the Martin Luther King Holiday Celebration Choir directed Aaron Staple.

(J. MILES CARY/NEWS SENTINEL )
Credit/Source: J. Miles Cary, J. Miles Cary/News Sentinel

Caption: Brittany Mosby, assistant math professor, lectures on statistics during her class at Pellissippi State Community College's Division Street Campus on Wednesday, Jan. 27, 2016. Instead of enrolling students who need extra math and English help into non-credit prerequisite classes before an intro class, the school is using a new approach of having students take both at once. (ADAM LAU/NEWS SENTINEL)

Jill Biden waves to the audience as she arrives to speak at Pellissippi State Community College, Friday, Jan. 9, 2015, in Knoxville, Tenn., about new initiatives to help more Americans go to college and get the skills they need to succeed. (AP Photo/Carolyn Kaster)
A delegation of 13 visitors from Russia joined Toni McDaniel's history class last month at Pellissippi State Community College.

Pellissippi State Community College students Haley Ann Candela, left, and Ashley Lawhorn work in the college's financial aid office at the Hardin Valley campus on Tuesday, February 4, 2014. The two are also Student Ambassadors, who provide help to incoming students with issues such as financial aid. Governor Bill Haslam proposed the "Tennessee Promise", a program that will provide two free years of community college or trade school for high school graduates.

(SAUL YOUNG/NEWS SENTINEL)

Pellissippi State Community College student Ashley Albritton stops for lunch at the college's Hardin Valley Campus on Tuesday, February 4, 2014. Albritton is a nursing student and single mother who is returned to college after more than a decade after her first attempt. Governor Bill Haslam proposed the "Tennessee Promise", a program that will provide two free years of community college or trade school for high school graduates.

(SAUL YOUNG/NEWS SENTINEL)

Tuesday, October 2, 2007

In this October 2, 2007 Knoxville News Sentinel attorney Richard Hollow listens as Knox County County Commissioner Greg Lumpy Lambert outlines his ideas on how the Knox County Commission can replace term limited officials.

Jurors today awarded News Sentinel Editor Jack McElroy and nine citizens a sweeping victory after a three-week trial that put 12 Knox Countians in judgment of their government.
The jury ruled that Knox County commissioners violated the Tennessee Open Meetings Act in setting in secret a specially called Jan. 31 meeting to replace 12 term-limited officeholders.  The jury also opined the commission did nothing to rectify that violation.  Jurors determined that commissioners decided in secret who would win all 12 of the term-limited seats left vacant after a Jan. 12 state Supreme Court ruling.

Date: Published 6:00 a.m. ET Feb. 3, 2019
Caption: Dave Ramsey (Photo: Ramsey Solutions)

PAY YOUR BILLS ON TIME: This may seem obvious, but even being slightly late, several times in a year could cause a creditor to report your delinquencies.  So make it a priority to pay your bills on time.

LEAVE PAID-OFF LOANS ON YOUR CREDIT REPORT:  This one seems counterintuitive because you would think getting rid of old paid off loans makes you look more responsible.  The truth is when creditors see that you paid well on old debt, it actually works to your advantage.

SHOP FOR A LOAN WITHIN A 30-DAY PERIOD: Every time you apply for credit, your score takes a small dip.  If you make multiple inquiries within 30 days, that will count as only one application since the credit reporting agencies will understand that you are shopping for one loan.  If you apply for credit more than 30 days apart then the credit agencies will conclude that you going for multiple loans, and your score will take a bigger hit.
KEEP WHAT YOU OWE BELOW 30 PERCENT OF YOUR CREDIT LIMIT: Don’t cancel paid up credit cards because it lowers your credit limit and makes it look like you have less available credit.

GO TO WWW.MYFICO.COM FOR MORE TIPS: This website is invaluable on knowing the percentages that are factored into your credit score.  It also gives suggestions on how to improve your score in the fastest possible way.

Caption: Terry Mattingly, News Sentinel columnist (Photo: Paul Efird / News Sentinel)
Doctor Who (Photo: giphy.com)

Nick Miles, 25, 6'1," supply chain director at Elkmont Exchange. Nick loves reading good books, but he is also an adventurer who enjoys trying new things - such as skiing down Breckenridge Mountain with no previous experience. His role models include his mother and George Clooney, who "developed a tequila brand, then sold it for a billion dollars." Nick appreciates anyone who can match his sarcasm and aims to visit New Zealand some day.

Curtis Glover, 35, 6'4," mural artist. You're probably familiar with Curtis from his large-scale murals all over Knoxville. He enjoys fishing, hiking and going to live shows. Although one of the first things people notice about him are his eyes, Curtis thinks one of his greatest assets is the solid work ethic he learned from his father. Curtis says he's "looking to develop authentic connections with the people he meets."

Mark Hazelwood, 35, 6'1," attorney. Mark plans fundraising events for Friends Who Love East Tennessee Children's Hospital and officiates at local high school football games. He is a solo practitioner at his own law firm, and his proudest accomplishment was winning his first jury trial. His dream job would be a travel writer. Mark says Taylor Swift is his guiltiest pleasure, and he would love to spend a day on the river with a date, blasting "Shake It Off."

Trason Williams, 38, 5'10," journeyman lineman with Knoxville Utilities Board. Trason loves kids and has a great sense of humor. He regularly volunteers for the Special Olympics via the United Way. Trason is something of a daredevil - a kayaker who practices Brazilian jiu jitsu - and he's more likely to take dates to a museum or a dance or cooking class than to a movie or a concert. He enjoys reading and watching the Food Network and documentaries about the Mafia.

Joshua Davenport, 31, 6', community crisis liaison at Helen Ross McNabb Center. Joshua's No. 1 goal is to be a good father to his daughter and he draws inspiration from his own father. He has "too many tattoos to count" and says that his vast wealth of useless facts makes him a fearsome competitor during trivia nights at local bars. Joshua loves cold beer and playing bass guitar and says that whether he hears a joke that's good or bad, he's probably still going to laugh.

Jake Hicks, 28, 5'8," photographer and assistant manager at Food City. Jake is originally from Cebu, the Philippines, and has a degree in graphic design and dreams of being a full-time photographer. He volunteers with Amachi Knoxville, mentoring young adults and children, and as an adopted child himself he learned the importance of strong role models. Jake is a dog lover with eclectic music tastes and is best described as "trendy, adventurous, friendly and an all-around gentleman."

Jesse Wade, 27, 5'10," licensed massage therapist at Longevity Massage Specialists and server at Kefi. A Tennessee native, Jesse is a musician, aspiring actor and trained in Brazilian jiu jitsu. He enjoys the outdoors - hiking, swimming and mountain biking - and loves spending time with Samantha, his German shepherd. The aspiring singer's most treasured possession is the 1978 Alvarez Yairi acoustic guitar given to him by his father.

Dean Marshall, 49, 5'11," loan officer for Foundation Mortgate. Knoxville-native Dean loves the change of seasons in East Tennessee. The father of two is all about family; he's inspired by his parents and says his great-grandfather's pocket watch is his most prized possession. He has been skydiving and hopes to go to Italy soon. He says he's searching fro "trust, friendship and quality time."

Chris Cook, 24, 6'1," financial counselor with 21st Mortgage. "Book nerd" Chris aspires to be an investment banker and was inspired by the perseverance of his single mom. Chris is a laidback guy with dreams of traveling to Italy. he spends his leisure time golfing, reading and indulging in coffee. He dreams of a happy family with the financial stability to "give graciously."

Joe Lybarger, 36, 6', doctoral teaching associate at the University of Tennessee. Joe's motto is "Life is one big adventure, and I want to see it all." The "brainy guy with a wild streak" rides his Harley-Davidson all over East Tennessee and crossbreeds rare orchids in his spare time. His interests range from classical music to monster movies, and he thinks East Tennessee has the most beautiful sunrises and sunsets of any place he has ever been.

After the parade the Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr. Memorial Service was held at the Warner Tabernacle AME Zion Church with  Rev. Dr. Charles E. Goodman, Jr., senior pastor of Tabernacle Baptist Church in Augusta, Ga., is the guest speaker.
Music by the Martin Luther King Holiday Celebration Choir directed Aaron Staple.

Caption: Many fast-food and casual-dining restaurants are offering deals for the Super Bowl. (Photo: Rasha Ali)
Taste testers try out Auntie Anne's mini pretzel dogs. (Photo: Rasha Ali, USA TODAY)

These Super Bowl snacks and desserts are bound to make your party guests rave, including this Mexican seven-layer dip. Serving dip can be less than appealing: after a few scoops are removed, it usually loses its neat layered look, and the serving spoon becomes a sticky mess. But not with these mini single servings.
If Applebee’s artichoke and spinach dip is one of your most-craved guilty pleasures, you’re going to love our Instant Pot copycat recipe for this amazing appetizer.
From football parties to Cinco de Mayo or even just TGIF, a big bowl of guac and chips is the perfect way to unwind when paired with a margarita or beer with lime.

Need a stunning yet simple appetizer to whet the appetites of your family and friends during the party? Serve this easy bacon jalapeño cheese ball, inspired by Divas Can Cook, with crackers and vegetables to give your family and friends an unforgettable finger food.

These spicy mini bacon cheeseballs are the perfect appetizer for every kind of party. We’ve taken the flavors of bacon-wrapped jalapeño poppers and changed them into an easier-to-make and super-fun-to-eat version.
Do you have a tableful of guests coming and need an impressive appetizer that whets their appetite for a meal? Let this baked Brie with blackberry compote be your go-to nibble.

If you’re looking for a new take on old traditions, look no further. These spiced nuts offer a peppy take on traditional flavors. If you love a treat that’s salty, sweet and savory — and with a bit of a punch — these nuts are the munchies you have been craving.

Want to surprise your party guests and serve a Louisiana seafood favorite? Chef Rusty’s chargrilled oysters will transport your taste buds to the Gulf Coast and forever change the way you eat this succulent mollusk.
